== <div style="background-color:rgba(173, 216, 230, 0.75); color: white; margin:1em; font-family:Futura text-shadow: 0 0 15px #0a7e8c, 0 0 35px Black, 0 0 40px Grey; padding:5px 10px; text-align:center; border-radius:4px;"><font size="6">Description</font></div> ==
{{Blurimage|file=141515126787.jpg|caption=“What is beyond?”.}}
'''Level 553''', also known as "Beyond Sun Burns" or "It Hurts", is an endless field stretching in every direction. The terrain is covered in green grass, hills and holes. The landscape doesn't have any landmarks which could make one disoriented.

The sky is always clear, with little to no clouds present. The only clouds observed are small Cumulus humilis clouds, which never produce rain.

A bright sun remains in the sky above the level. It never moves and only remain directly above the level. It shines around fifteen times brighter than the sun in the [[Frontrooms]] and produces extreme heat. Surface temperatures typically range between 40°C and 60°C (104°F or 140°F), making exposure dangerous. The sun is capable of changing color, and these changes are considered the primary environmental hazard within the level.

Despite the extreme temperatures, the vegetation appears unaffected. Most of the grass remains green and healthy, although some areas may gradually turn yellow. Bushes are scattered across the field without any pattern.

Trees are fairly common and are usually visible from almost any location. Most resemble oak trees and vary greatly in height and size. Two or more trees might merge together, forming a single unusually large tree. This could form large forest like areas randomly throughout the level.

High levels of radiation have also been detected throughout the level. 

== <div style="background-color:rgba(173, 216, 230, 0.75); color: white; margin:1em; font-family:Futura text-shadow: 0 0 15px #0a7e8c, 0 0 35px Black, 0 0 40px Grey; padding:5px 10px; text-align:center; border-radius:4px;"><font size="6">Environment</font></div> ==
Level 553's environment is mainly controlled by the sun, primarily the sun's color. Each color has its own meaning and danger. The colors range from red to blue. The sky also changes color to match whatever the sun's color is. The danger is rated from 1/5 (Livable) to 5/5 (Deadzone).
{{Underline|FFFFFF}}
{| style="background:#FF3046; color: #191919"
|-
|<span style="font-size:150%">'''4/5'''</span>
|'''Common'''
When the sun turns red, it usually indicates that it will begin producing extremely high levels of heat and radiation. During this phase, temperatures across the level may rise significantly above the normal range, making prolonged exposure far more dangerous. The main characteristic of this event is the sky turning a deep dark red color, often accompanied by the complete disappearance of clouds. The atmosphere may also appear slightly distorted due to intense heat rising from the ground.

It is strongly recommended that wanderers take cover under large oak trees or inside large bushes during this period. While this does not completely block the heat or radiation, it can slightly reduce direct exposure from the sun and may prevent severe burns or radiation-related symptoms.
|}
{| style="background:#FF8237; color: #191919"
|-
|<span style="font-size:150%">'''3/5'''</span>
|'''Very Common'''
When a wanderer first enters the level, the sun will usually appear as a bright orange color. During this phase, both heat and radiation levels remain relatively normal compared to other phases of the level. Temperatures typically stay within the standard range of the environment, and radiation exposure does not immediately pose a serious threat to wanderers.

This phase can remain up to four hours at a time. During this period, the sky will often appear light orange, reflecting the sun's color. Environmental conditions are generally stable, making this one of the safer periods within the level for travel and exploration. However, wanderers should remain cautious, as the sun's color can change without warning.
|}
{| style="background:#FACF43; color: #191919"
|-
|<span style="font-size:150%">'''2/5'''</span>
|'''Uncommon'''
When the sun turns yellow, it usually indicates that the temperature within the level is beginning to drop. During this phase, the environment becomes noticeably cooler compared to the other sun phases. Temperatures typically remain within a moderate range of 18°C (64.4°F) to 27°C (80.6°F), making this one of the more comfortable periods for wanderers. Radiation levels generally remain at normal levels, though in some cases they may rise slightly above standard levels.

One unusual effect of this phase is the rapid growth of vegetation. The grass begins to grow at an unnatural pace, sometimes reaching heights of up to 1.4 meters (4.5 ft) within a relatively short period of time. This rapid growth can make movement more difficult in certain areas, as tall grass may obscure holes in the ground or other terrain hazards.

Despite the calmer environmental conditions, wanderers are still advised to remain cautious, as the sun may change color again without warning.
|}
{| style="background:#93DC5C; color: #191919"
|-
|<span style="font-size:150%">'''1/5'''</span>
|'''Rare'''
When the sun turns green, it indicates that the temperature and overall environment are relatively safe for exploration. During this phase, the level presents little to no immediate danger to wanderers. The weather becomes more active, and rain is possible. In some cases, large and complex thunderstorms may form, bringing heavy rain and hail across the field.

The temperature during this phase usually ranges between 12°C and 18°C (53.6°F–64.4°F), making it one of the cooler and more comfortable periods within the level. Vegetation also grows rapidly during this time. Grass and other plants may reach heights of up to 1.7 meters (5.5 ft), sometimes forming dense patches that can make navigation more difficult for wanderers.
|}
{| style="background:#0A6ED3; color: #191919"
|-
|<span style="font-size:150%">'''5/5'''</span>
|'''Very Rare'''
The blue phase is regarded as the most dangerous phase of all. During this phase, very large supercells begin to form across the level, often resembling conditions similar to major tornado outbreaks. These storms are extremely violent and can develop rapidly across the open fields.

The supercells produce very large hail, sometimes reaching around 5 cm (2 inches) in diameter. Heavy rainfall is also common during this phase, significantly reducing visibility for wanderers and making navigation extremely difficult. In addition to the hail and rain, the storms are capable of producing violent tornadoes.

These tornadoes can reach EF5 or F5 intensity and might grow up to 4 km (2.4 miles) wide. The tornadoes are powerful enough to rip trees out of the ground and leave deep scars across the terrain. Wind speeds inside the strongest tornadoes have been measured at around 250 to 350 mph.
|}
